 that EU-level developments increasingly interact with social protection in all countries - a remarkable transformation from ten years ago. Using the same thematic framework, the book systematically compares how Europeanisation of social protection differs across countries chosen to reflect increasing EU diversity. For each country, specialists in social protection evaluate the form and extent of Europeanisation, comparing national strategies with the European social model. They examine recent reforms and responses to EU initiatives, including the Lisbon strategy and the open method of coordination, the extension of the internal market to services, the Economic and Monetary Union and EU enlargement. Differences in Europeanisation reflect not only different political legacies but also different adjustment pressures in terms of national welfare regime and degree of competitiveness. Europeanisation of social protection brings together both new evidence and new perspectives, making it essential reading for everyone interested in the changing patterns of social policy in Europe.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aPublic welfarexCongressesxEuropean Union countries. 0aPublic welfarezEuropean Union countriesvCongresses. 0aSocial changexCongressesxEuropean Union countries. 0aSocial changezEuropean Union countriesvCongresses. 0aSocial planningxCongressesxEuropean Union countries. 0aSocial planningzEuropean Union countriesvCongresses. 0aSocial securityxCongressesxEuropean Union countries. 0aSocial securityzEuropean Union countriesvCongresses. 0aWelfare statexCongressesxEuropean Union countries. 0aWelfare statezEuropean Union countriesvCongresses. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Social Services & Welfare.2bisacsh1 aBüchs, Milena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relato